<h3>Step 2: Getting to Vicchio</h3>
<p>Once you make it to Florence, you have two options. You can rent a car and drive the last hour, or you can take the local train.</p>
<p>The villa is 15 mins from the train station so a cab or someone in the group with a car can pick you up. Taking the train from Florence is probably the right option for some, but we also need a few cars in the group so we can explore and get around easily.</p>
<p>The two of us will be in the area early and will have a rental car of our own.</p>

<h3>Notes for those Renting a Car</h3>
<p>1) Get your IDP (International Driving Permit). You will need to fill out an application, pay $20 and provide two passport sized photos.<br><a href="https://northeast.aaa.com/travel/plan-your-trip/international-driving-permit.html">Link to online IDP application</a></p>
<p>2) Reserve your car in advance for a better price. Most rentals are MANUAL, so especially rent far in advance and be prepared to pay slightly extra for an automatic.</p>
<p>3) Get the insurance!</p>
<p>4) Read some articles about driving in Italy in general. For example, the left lane is for passing ONLY and this is strictly adhered to in Italy (Keeley says I love to sit in the left lane...)</p>
<p>5) If you are feeling adventurous and get a car for more than just the local Vicchio area have fun but do NOT drive in Rome. Apparently it's insane. The country roads of Tuscany will be much more manageable.</p>

